<HL>
   Airbus Signs Accord
   To Sell 2 Types of Jet
   To Taiwanese Carrier
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   U.BA F.ABI F.ASP G.MES
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
AIRLINES (AIR)
</IN>
<LP>
   PARIS -- Airbus Industrie said it signed a firm contract
to sell two A320 aircraft and four A300-600R aircraft to
Foshing Airlines of Taiwan, which also took options to buy
four other A300-600Rs.
   Airbus didn't give financial details of the order, but
industry sources estimate that one A320 costs about $40
million and that an A300-600R costs a little more than $77
million. Prices vary depending on the spare parts and
training selected by the customer.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Airbus said deliveries to Foshing of the A320s, to be
powered by International Aero Engines V2500 engines, will
begin in 1992. The A300-600Rs, equipped with Pratt &amp; Whitney
PW-4000s, will arrive in 1994.
   Firm orders for the Airbus's A300 and A310 aircraft now
total 657 from 78 customers, while orders for A320s and A321s
stand at 707 from 33 customers.
   Airbus is a consortium of Aerospatiale of France,
Messerschmitt-Boelkow-Blohm G.m.b.H. of West Germany, British
Aerospace PLC and Construcciones Aeronauticas S.A. of Spain.
</TEXT>
