<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
09/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   WORLD OIL PRICES SURGED on pessimism over the Mideast
crisis and the outlook for winter supplies. Speculative
buying helped push some crude prices beyond $31 a barrel. The
jump came even as some small producers planned to follow OPEC
in raising output. Stocks fell, with the Dow Jones
industrials drop ping 31.93 points to 2596.29. Tokyo and
London shares declined as well.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Equimark's Alan Fellheimer resigned as chairman of the
troubled bank holding concern. The move follows the Tisch
family's disclosure that it holds a 6.8% stake in the firm.
   ---
   Franklin Savings' return to its previous management from
control of federal regulators was blocked by a U.S. court's
temporary stay.
   ---
   The major U.S. retailers posted modest sales gains. But
analysts say weakness in home furnishings and early fall
merchandise indicate diffi culties through the winter season.
   ---
   U.S. businesses are paring capital-spending plans because
of growing concern about the economy, the latest Commerce
Department survey in dicates. Outlays for 1990 are now ex
pected to increase 5.4%, down from the previous estimate of
6.8%.
   ---
   G-7 officials will meet in Paris next week to discuss the
dollar's recent decline and consider if actions are needed to
bolster the currency.
   ---
   U.S. bank earnings fell 24% in the second quarter to $5.3
billion, largely on a $1.9 billion jump in Northeastern
institutions' loan-loss reserves. Bad real estate loans
remain the major problem for the industry.
   ---
   Both parties' leaders vowed to present separate $50
billion deficit-reduction packages as their opening bids in
renewed budget talks today.
   ---
   Motorola plans to start shipping its much-delayed 68040
microproces sor in October. The delays have in turn set back
production at computer makers that rely on the chip.
   ---
   Lotus Development is issuing the latest upgrade to its
1-2-3 spread sheet, a move that could help reverse the
company's earnings difficulties.
                                                                                                       

   IBM announced a joint venture with Metaphor Computer to
produce an underlying layer of software aimed at speeding
development of personal-computer software uses.
   ---
   L.A. Gear expects to post fiscal third-quarter profit
below that of a year ago, when the sneaker maker reported a
record net of $22 million.
   ---
   Goodyear expects to post a third-quarter loss of about $65
million mostly related to 1,180 planned layoffs in its
European operations. The tire maker also expressed concern
over adverse effects on raw material costs due to the Mideast
crisis.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 125,620,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2596.29, off 31.93; transportation 892.20, off 5.54;
utilities 198.25, off 0.19.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3350.65, up
5.68.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.55, up 0.37; spot
index 130.10, up 0.13.
   Dollar: 140.70 yen, off 1.00; 1.5550 marks, off 0.0035.
